<search>legal and political effects of the Dred Scott decision</search>

<information>The decision had several legal and political effects. In legal terms, it ruled that African Americans, whether enslaved or free, could not be American citizens and therefore had no standing to sue in federal court. It also ruled that the U.S. Constitution did not authorize Congress to prohibit slavery in U.S. territories. Politically, the decision was highly controversial and contributed to the growing divide between the Northern and Southern United States, eventually leading to the American Civil War.</information>

